Aslong as the temps are fine you can use almost any liquid that doesnt dissolve your seals.

snippet.textDisplay:
After seeing seth post about doing this a year ago i decided to do the same experiment on my bike (Trek remedy 9 with shimano XT brakes front and rear). Well 9 months and about 1500 miles later (i ride a lot) the seals in the lever gave way leading to the dredded leaver stick problem where the piston goes in and stays in. I have since replaced the brakes with new ones (some more XT's, Lever, hose and caliper) and filled with proper mineral oil. So, in conclusion, on a bike that got a lot of use in XC and Enduro riding (with a good bit of downhill too) the baby oil seems to work for a bit till it destroys your seals and kills the breaks for good. Cannot recommend.


EDIT: and yeah on uplift days the oil would get pretty hot and stink of baby oil fragrance really strongly

Maybe it was mentioned in the other video, but please do not do this with DOT4 or DOT5.1 brake fluid systems as you will really mess the seals up.
If you are in a pinch needing a quick fix on the trail, you can use water with DOT fluid and it won't wreck the seals, just mind the brake boiling. For mineral fluid systems, stick with basic oils in emergencies.

snippet.textDisplay: Brake fluid is specifically designed to be anti-foaming above anything else. Foaming in your breaks is very bad. In a small application like a bike where there is no brake booster as in a car, its probably fine. Whatever you do don't use this in a car. Baby oil will cause foam in your lines and you will lose your brakes because of this.

snippet.textDisplay: It's very simple. In order to have a "warranty" the company that manufactures the brake must use consistent parts. The brake fluid is part of this equation. Baby oil/Mineral oil can vary measurably from brand to brand. Hence, it can NOT be "recommended" in cases where warranty is an issue. That being said... I've raced the hell out of Johnson's and it works fine. But... just like changing pad and rotor material, the viscosity (thickness) of the oil will have an effect. If you are fighting for 10th's of a second, it will make a difference. If you are low on funds or want to save a trip, it is 100% legit. It has never failed any of my Magura brakes. And yes, I actually do spend the extra few cents to get a quality name brand "baby oil."

snippet.textDisplay:
Hi Seth, well I worked for some Brake manufacturers in the past and was involved in the R&D of some Nixe products over the years. Most mineral oil brakes use the same materials for their seals, Membran or even the piston, so you can run all sorts of mineral oil without demaging the brakes.
Clearly the boiling temperature is the most important difference between cheap oils and some racing oils used by their teams or in WRX (Not in the brakes but the gear boxes). So yes Baby oil will Do the Job for 95% of the riders. Legal notice every Brand has to narrow down some options to denie warranties... (only use Brand x oil) otherwise it would be imposibile to garanty their function.
You may Do a simple boiling test to See the Main difference between them.
